{"title_page": "A Written Testimony", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = A Written Testimony\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Jay Electronica]]\n| cover        = A Written Testimony cover art.jpg\n| border       = yes\n| alt          = \n| released     = March 13, 2020<ref name=\"NewRelease\"/>\n| recorded     = December 26, 2019 \u2013 February 6, 2020{{efn|Except \"Shiny Suit Theory\", recorded in November 2010}}\n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length       = 39:34\n| label        = [[Roc Nation]]\n| producer     =\n* Jay Electronica\n* [[Swizz Beatz]]\n* [[Hit-Boy]]\n* [[The Alchemist (musician)|The Alchemist]]\n* [[No I.D.]]\n* [[Khruangbin]]\n| year         = 2020\n| prev_title   = [[Act I: Eternal Sunshine (The Pledge)]]\n| prev_year    = 2007\n| next_title   =\n| next_year    =\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = A Written Testimony\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Shiny Suit Theory]]\n | single1date = November 15, 2010\n}}\n}}\n'''''A Written Testimony''''' ([[Arabic language|Arabic]]: ''\u0634\u0647\u0627\u062f\u0629 \u0645\u0643\u062a\u0648\u0628\u0629'') is the  debut studio album by American rapper [[Jay Electronica]]. The album was primarily recorded in 40 days, from December 2019 to February 2020, and was released on March 13, 2020. The album follows the release of his debut mixtape, ''[[Act I: Eternal Sunshine (The Pledge)]]'', almost 13 years earlier. Most of the album's tracks feature uncredited vocals by [[Jay-Z]], while [[Travis Scott]] and [[The-Dream]] make guest appearances. Production was primarily handled by Jay Electronica, who is credited on six out of ten tracks, along with [[Swizz Beats]], [[Hit-Boy]], [[No I.D.]], and [[Khruangbin]], among others.\n\n==Background and recording==\n[[File:Jay Electronica.jpg|thumb|left|Jay Electronica first announced a follow-up to ''[[Act I: Eternal Sunshine (The Pledge)]]'' in 2007, but didn't complete ''A Written Testimony'' until early 2020.]]\nJay Electronica's debut project ''[[Act I: Eternal Sunshine (The Pledge)]]'', released in July 2007, was meant to be the first part of a [[trilogy]], with the other planned installments being entitled ''Act II: Patents of Nobility (The Turn)'' and ''Act III: The Last Will & Testament of Timothy Elpadaro Thedford (The Prestige)''.<ref name=\"Vice\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/6ed3xk/the-prestige-the-five-percenters-and-why-jay-electronica-hasnt-released-his-debut-album|author=Ryan Bassil|date=October 23, 2013|accessdate=February 7, 2020|website=[[Vice Media|Vice UK]]|title=The Prestige, The Five Percenters, and Why Jay Electronica Hasn\u2019t Released His Debut Album}}</ref> In September 2007, Jay Electronica indicated that he planned to create ''Act II'' and ''Act III''.<ref name=\"2007Interview\">{{Cite web|date=September 27, 2007|accessdate=February 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121209081525/http://wmdeez.wordpress.com/2007/09/25/jay-electronica-interview/|archive-date=December 9, 2012|title=Jay Electronica Interview|website=Weapons of Mass Distraction|author=Andres Reyes|url=http://wmdeez.wordpress.com/2007/09/25/jay-electronica-interview/|url-status=dead}}</ref> Following the official release of his hit single \"[[Exhibit C]]\", Jay Electronica announced on [[Shade 45]] that ''Act II'' would be released on [[Christmas Day]] 2009; producer [[Just Blaze]] confirmed that the album would miss this date.<ref name=\"Timeline\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/jay-electronica-debut-album-timeline|title=The Long Road to Jay Electronica\u2019s Debut Album|date=February 25, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|author=Brad Callas}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, Jay Electronica stated that he was planning on doing collaborative projects with rappers [[Mos Def]], [[Lupe Fiasco]], and [[Nas]].<ref name=\"History\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/a-written-testimony-the-road-to-jay-electronicas-debut-album-news.103687.html|title=A Written Testimony: The Road To Jay Electronica's Debut Album|author=Robert Blair|date=February 15, 2020|accessdate=February 15, 2020|website=HotNewHipHop|archive-date=February 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215192545/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/a-written-testimony-the-road-to-jay-electronicas-debut-album-news.103687.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In August 2010, Jay Electronica stated that ''Act II'' would be released on his birthday September 19, 2010.<ref name=\"Timeline\"/> In November 2010, Jay Electronica signed to [[Roc Nation]] and released his first collaborative song with [[Jay-Z]], entitled \"[[Shiny Suit Theory]]\".<ref name=\"Timeline\"/><ref name=\"History\"/>\n\nJay Electronica announced that ''Act II'' was completed in 2011 and later shared a track list in 2012.<ref name=\"Vice\"/> The track list included guest appearances from Jay-Z, [[Kanye West]], [[Charlotte Gainsbourg]], [[The-Dream]], and [[Sean Combs]], among others.<ref name=\"Act2Tracks\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/47298-jay-electronica-shares-album-tracklist/|title=Jay Electronica Shares Album Tracklist|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=July 28, 2012|accessdate=February 7, 2020|author=Evan Minsker}}</ref> The album was never released.<ref name=\"Vice\"/> In 2013, Jay Electronica intended to include the song \"[[Control (Big Sean song)|Control]]\" on his album after [[Big Sean]] removed it from ''[[Hall of Fame (Big Sean album)|Hall of Fame]]''.<ref name=\"Control\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/52118-jay-electronica-wanted-control-for-his-album/|title=Jay Electronica Wanted \"Control\" for His Album|date=September 1, 2013|accessdate=February 16, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|author=Evan Minsker|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411203730/https://pitchfork.com/news/52118-jay-electronica-wanted-control-for-his-album/|archive-date=April 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> However, Big Sean instead released the song as a promotional single after [[Kendrick Lamar]] recorded his controversial verse for the song.<ref name=\"Control\"/> In 2014, Jay Electronica again announced that his album would be releasing that year.<ref name=\"History\"/> In 2017, Jay Electronica denounced the traditional roll-out of studio albums, stating \"[a]n album is something that was created by corporations as a product to make money.\"<ref name=\"History\"/>\n\nIn March 2019, Jay Electronica teased on [[Instagram]] that he may work with Jay-Z on his album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8503490/jay-electronica-teases-possible-jay-z-joint-collboration|title=Jay Electronica Hints at Possible Collaboration With Jay-Z|date=March 21, 2019|accessdate=February 7, 2020|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|author=Michael Saponara}}</ref> In April 2019, Zachary Schwartz of DJ Booth speculated that the collaborative album was ''Act III''.<ref name=\"Schwartz\">{{Cite web|url=https://djbooth.net/features/2019-04-05-jay-electronica-act-ii-found-in-plain-sight|title=We Found Jay Electronica\u2019s 'Act II'\u2014It\u2019s Been Hiding in Plain Sight|author=Zachary Schwartz|website=DJBooth|date=April 12, 2019|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref> On February 6, 2020, Jay Electronica announced that he completed his debut album ''A Written Testimony''.<ref name=\"Announce\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/jay-electronica-says-his-new-album-is-out-in-40-days/|title=Jay Electronica Says His New Album Is Out in 40 Days|author=Evan Minsker|date=February 7, 2020|accessdate=February 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207171923/https://pitchfork.com/news/jay-electronica-says-his-new-album-is-out-in-40-days/|archive-date=February 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Jay Electronica recorded the album in \"40 days and 40 nights\", beginning on December 26, 2019.<ref name=\"Announce\"/> Jay Electronica and Jay-Z recorded the final track \"A.P.I.D.T.A.\" on the night of January 26, 2020, when former NBA player [[Kobe Bryant]] died in a [[2020 Calabasas helicopter crash|helicopter crash]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/jay-electronica-jay-z-apidta-night-kobe-bryant-died|title=Jay Electronica and JAY-Z Made the Song \u201cA.P.I.D.T.A.\u201d on the Night Kobe Bryant Died|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020|author=Tara C. Mahadevan|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314140504/https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/jay-electronica-jay-z-apidta-night-kobe-bryant-died|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Jay Electronica set an initial release date of March 18, 2020, 40 days after recording was completed.<ref name=\"Announce\"/> In February 2020, radio host [[Angela Yee]], who formerly managed Jay Electronica, confirmed on ''[[The Breakfast Club (radio show)|The Breakfast Club]]'' that she had listened to the album and that \"Jay-Z is on much of the album.\"<ref name=\"Yee\">{{Cite web|url=https://allhiphop.com/news/angela-yee-confirms-jay-z-appears-on-much-of-jay-electronica-s-album-gives-details-about-the-release-IR-cXbZZs02obOyMZpEvBg|title=Angela Yee Confirms Jay-Z Appears On Much Of Jay Electronica's Album & Gives Details About The Release|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 15, 2020|author=Yohance Kyles|website=AllHipHop|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213204831/https://allhiphop.com/news/angela-yee-confirms-jay-z-appears-on-much-of-jay-electronica-s-album-gives-details-about-the-release-IR-cXbZZs02obOyMZpEvBg|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Release and promotion==\n[[File:A Written Testimony listening party poster.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Listening parties for the album were cancelled due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic]] (poster pictured).]]\nOn February 6, 2020, Jay Electronica announced ''A Written Testimony'' with a March 18, 2020 release date.<ref name=\"Announce\"/> In anticipation of the album's release, record producer [[Young Guru]] posted a picture of himself in the studio with Jay Electronica, Jay-Z and Lawrence \"Law\" Parker on March 10, 2020.<ref name=\"Parties\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/jay-electronica-jay-z-studio-pic-fuels-debut-album-anticipation|title=Tidal Announces Listening Events for Jay Electronica's Debut Album 'A Written Testimony' (UPDATE)|author=Joshua Espinoza|date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 11, 2020|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]}}</ref> That same day, [[Streaming media|streaming]] service [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]] announced three listening parties for the album.<ref name=\"Parties\"/> Tidal planned to host the listening parties on March 12 in [[Los Angeles]], [[New York City]], and Jay Electronica's hometown of [[New Orleans]].<ref name=\"Parties\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9332435/jay-electronica-a-written-testimony-tidal-listening-sessions|title=Jay Electronica Album Listening Sessions Are Finally Happening in These Cities|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=March 11, 2020|date=March 11, 2020|author=Carl Lamarre|url-status=live|archive-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311224551/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9332435/jay-electronica-a-written-testimony-tidal-listening-sessions}}</ref> On March 11, 2020, Yee confirmed on ''The Breakfast Club'' that the album would be released on March 13, 2020 after the listening parties.<ref name=\"NewRelease\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2ohlDtYcaAQ|title=6ix9ine's Prison Release Date Has Been Set Early For Being A 'Model Prisoner'|website=[[YouTube]]|author=[[The Breakfast Club (radio show)|The Breakfast Club]]|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On March 12, 2020, [[Apple Music]] revealed the track listing for ''A Written Testimony'' through [[Twitter]]. The track listing, written in the [[Arabic language]], included ten tracks with [[guest appearance]]s from [[Travis Scott]] and The-Dream.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/jay-electronica-a-written-testimony-tracklist|title=Jay Electronica Shares Tracklist for Upcoming Debut Album 'A Written Testimony'|author=Tara C. Mahadevan|publisher=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Tracklist\">{{cite web|url=https://hiphop-n-more.com/2020/03/jay-electronica-a-written-testimony-track-list-stream/|title=Jay Electronica Reveals 'A Written Testimony' Track List|website=HipHop-N-More|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/everything-we-know-about-jay-electronica-s-new-album-a-written-testimony-cover-art-tracklist-features-producers-release-date|title=Here\u2019s Everything We Know About Jay Electronica\u2019s New Album \u2018A Written Testimony\u2019|website=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> After the track list was revealed, the listening parties were cancelled due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic]] and Tidal revealed the album's cover art.<ref name=\"Tracklist\"/>\n\nIn November 2010, Jay Electronica released his first collaborative song with Jay-Z entitled \"Shiny Suit Theory\" after signing to Roc Nation.<ref name=\"History\"/> In July 2012, a track list for ''Act II: Patents of Nobility (The Turn)'' was revealed that included a song titled \"Dinner at Tiffanys (The Shiny Suit Theory)\" featuring Gainsbourg, Jay-Z and The-Dream.<ref name=\"Act2Tracks\"/> In September 2018, the original version of the song was rereleased exclusively to Tidal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hiphop-n-more.com/2018/09/jay-electronica-officially-releases-shiny-suit-theory-feat-jay-z-the-dream/|title=Jay Electronica Officially Releases 'Shiny Suit Theory' Feat. Jay-Z & The-Dream|publisher=HipHop-N-More|date=September 17, 2018|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The song was included on the track list for ''A Written Testimony'' revealed in March 2020, with only The-Dream listed as a featured artist.<ref name=\"Tracklist\"/>\n\n==Controversy==\n[[File:Louis Farrakhan 2018.jpg|thumb|left|200px|[[Louis Farrakhan]], who has been designated as a hate extremist by the [[Southern Poverty Law Center|SPLC]], is featured on the album.]]\nOn the track \"The Ghost of Soulja Slim\", Jay Electronica references the [[Synagogue of Satan]] and his ex-girlfriend [[Kate Rothschild]].<ref name=\"Rosenberg\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/peter-rosenberg-responds-to-jay-electronica-synagogue-of-satan-lyric|title=Peter Rosenberg Speaks More on Jay Electronica Defending 'Synagogue of Satan' Lyric|author=FNR Tigg|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Jay Electronica had previously rapped about the Synagogue of Satan on 2014 track \"Better Tune in with the Infinite\".<ref name=\"Rosenberg\"/> Rothschild has also been the subject of multiple [[Anti-Semitism|anti-Semitic]] conspiracy theories.<ref name=\"JP\"/> American radio personality [[Peter Rosenberg]] accused Jay Electronica of anti-Semitism for his Synagogue of Satan references.<ref name=\"Rosenberg\"/> Jay Electronica responded by accusing Rosenberg of \"clout chasing\" and invited him to a public forum with theological scholars to discuss the lyrics.<ref name=\"Rosenberg\"/> Jay Electronica also stated that he stood behind \"every single word\" on the album.<ref name=\"Rosenberg\"/> FNR Tigg of ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' defended \"The Ghost of Soulja Slim\", writing that the particular line was not anti-Semetic but that Jay Electronica was \"finding a clever way to vent about a personal vendetta he had against [Rothschild] who he feels aided in helping the media assassinate his character.\"<ref name=\"Rosenberg\"/>\n\nLee Harpin of ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]'' also noted the lyrics \"Satan struck [[State of Palestine|Palestine]] with yet another mortar\" from the track \"Fruits of the Spirit\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/world/new-hip-hop-jay-electronica-album-antisemitism-storm-synagogue-of-satan-louis-farrakhan-1.498215|title=New hip hop album causes antisemitism storm with 'synagogue of Satan' reference|author=Lee Harpin|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020|website=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]}}</ref> Gabe Friedman of ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'' highlighted the album's inclusion of vocals from [[Louis Farrakhan]],<ref name=\"JP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Antisemitism/Rapper-Jay-Electronica-sparks-antisemitism-controversy-621379|title=Rapper Jay Electronica sparks antisemitism controversy|website=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020|author=Gabe Friedman}}</ref> the leader of the [[Nation of Islam]] who has been labelled as an extremist by the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] due to anti-Semitic and [[Black supremacy|black supremacist]] views.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/extremist-files/individual/louis-farrakhan|title=Louis Farrakhan \u2013 Southern Poverty Law Center|website=[[Southern Poverty Law Center]]|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Featured artist Jay-Z has also been previously cautioned by the [[Anti-Defamation League]] in 2017 for controversial lyrics.<ref name=\"JP\"/>\n\nSoon after release, Jay Electronica was also embroiled in an online dispute with American rapper-journalist [[Joe Budden]].<ref name=\"Budden\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/jay-electronica-joe-budden-beef/|title=Jay Electronica & Joe Budden Have Beef Over 'A Written Testimony'|accessdate=March 20, 2020|date=March 18, 2020|author=Feleg Tesema|website=[[Highsnobiety]]}}</ref> On his podcast, Budden criticized the album and stated that \"Jay Electronica got smacked around by JAY-Z\".<ref name=\"Budden\"/> Jay Electronica reacted by denouncing Budden's rap career, however an old video recorded by Yee surfaced that showed Jay Electronica praising Budden as an [[Master of ceremonies|MC]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.okayplayer.com/news/joe-budden-jay-electronica-twitter-feud.html|title=Joe Budden Addresses Jay Electronica Twitter Back And Forth On Podcast|author=Elijah C. Watson|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020|website=OkayPlayer}}</ref>\n{{clear}}<!--Only pushes down by one line-->\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 85/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/a-written-testimony/jay-electronica|title=A Written Testimony by Jay Electronica Reviews and Tracks|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/a-written-testimony-mw0003368165|title=A Written Testimony \u2013 Jay Electronica|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|last=Thomas|first=Fred|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev2score = A\u2212<ref name=\"COS\">{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/03/album-review-jay-electronica-a-written-testimony/|title=Jay Electronica Finally Delivers on A Written Testimony|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=Grove|first=Rashad|date=March 15, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3score = B+<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/music/music-reviews/jay-electronica-a-written-testimony-ew-review/|title=Jay Electronica's A Written Testimony is a righteous step forward: Review|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Moore|first=Marcus J.|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev4score = 7/10<ref name=\"exclaim\">{{cite web|url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/jay_electronica-a_written_testimony|title=Jay Electronica: A Written Testimony|website=[[Exclaim!]]|last=Harmony|first=A.|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[HipHopDX]]''\n| rev5score = 4.0/5<ref name=\"HHDX\">{{cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/reviews/id.3636/title.review-jay-electronica-basks-in-jay-zs-shadow-on-debut-album-a-written-testimony|title=Review: Jay Electronica Basks In JAY-Z's Shadow On Debut Album 'A Written Testimony'|website=[[HipHopDX]]|last=Kenny|first=Brody|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/jay-electronica-a-written-testimony-review-2626202|title=Jay Electronica \u2013 'A Written Testimony' review: mythical rapper's Jay-Z collab isn't the revelation fans had hoped for|website=[[NME]]|last=Balram|first=Dhruva|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7score = 8.4/10<ref name=\"pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/jay-electronica-a-written-testimony/|title=Jay Electronica: A Written Testimony Album Review|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Pearce|first=Sheldon|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n''A Written Testimony'' was met with widespread acclaim from critics. At Metacritic, which assigns a weighted average rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, this release received an average score of 85, based on nine reviews.<ref name=\"MC\"/>\n\nRashad Grove of ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' praised the album as \"one hell of a promising effort that was well worth the wait\", further stating, \"The skillset of Jay Electronica as both an MC and a producer is on full display, even when he does seemingly play [[Robin (character)|Robin]] to Jay-Z's [[Batman|Dark Knight]] on his own project.\"<ref name=\"COS\"/> A. Harmony of ''[[Exclaim!]]'' hailed it as \"a solid effort that makes good on promises set by Electronica's earlier work: thumping, vintage beats; dense rhymes that shimmer with vivid imagery; clever references to the Nation of Islam.\"<ref name=\"exclaim\"/> ''[[HipHopDX]]''{{'s}} Brody Kenny felt that the album was worth the anticipation, describing it as a \"summation of why so many people have revered Jay Electronica for so long.\"<ref name=\"HHDX\"/> Writing for ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', Marcus J. Moore called it \"an accomplished album with decent rewind factor, but it feels somewhat hampered by the seismic impact of the rapper's work a decade ago.\"<ref name=\"EW\"/> In his review for ''[[NME]]'', Dhruva Balram noted that Jay Electronica and Jay-Z \"exchange epic verses in a style that's inevitably similar to [[Raekwon]] and [[Ghostface Killah]] on ''[[Only Built 4 Cuban Linx...|Only Built 4 Cuban Linx]]''\", however, he concluded that the album \"is nothing spectacular; it won't shift or affect cultural discourse.\"<ref name=\"NME\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Track listing==\nCredits are adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref name=\"Tidal\">{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/134189334/credits|title=Credits / A Written Testimony / J A Y E L E C T R O N I C A|publisher=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 39:34\n| title_width = 30%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| extra_width = 20%\n\n| title1 = The Overwhelming Event\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Louis Farrakhan]]|[[1500 or Nothin'|Larrance Dopson]]|Khirye Tyler|[[Eric Demarsan]]}}\n| extra1 = [[Jay Electronica]]\n| length1  = 2:17\n\n| title2 = Ghost of Soulja Slim\n| writer2 = {{hlist|[[Jay Electronica|Elpadaro Allah]]|[[Jay-Z|Shawn Carter]]|Farrakhan|[[Soulja Slim|James Tapp]]|[[KLC|Craig Lawson]]|John Williams|Dopson|Tyler|Chris Payton}}\n| extra2 = Jay Electronica\n| length2  = 4:26\n\n| title3 = The Blinding\n| note3  = featuring [[Travis Scott]]\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Allah|[[Travis Scott|Jacques Webster]]|Carter|[[Swizz Beatz|Kasseem Dean]]|[[Hit-Boy|Chauncey Hollis]]|[[AraabMuzik|Abraham Orellana]]|[[PartyNextDoor|Jahron Brathwaite]]}}\n| extra3 = {{hlist|[[Swizz Beatz]]|[[Hit-Boy]]|[[AraabMuzik]]{{ref|a|[a]}}|G. Ry{{ref|a|[a]}}}}\n| length3  = 2:49\n\n| title4 = The Neverending Story \n| writer4 = {{hlist|Allah|Carter|[[The-Dream|Terius Nash]]|[[The Alchemist (musician)|Daniel Alan Maman]]|[[Litto Nebbia|Felix Nebbia]]|Mirtha Defilpo}}\n| extra4 = [[The Alchemist (musician)|The Alchemist]]\n| length4  = 4:21\n\n| title5 = [[Shiny Suit Theory]]\n| note5  = featuring [[The-Dream]]\n| writer5 = {{hlist|Allah|Nash|Carter|[[Barbara Mason]]}}\n| extra5 = Jay Electronica\n| length5  = 4:04\n\n| title6 = Universal Soldier\n| writer6 = {{hlist|Allah|Carter|Webster|[[James Blake (musician)|James Blake Litherland]]|[[Vashti Bunyan|Jennifer Vashti Bunyan]]|[[Allen Toussaint]]}}\n| extra6 = Jay Electronica\n| length6  = 4:19\n\n| title7 = Flux Capacitor\n| writer7 = {{hlist|Allah|Carter|[[Rihanna|Robyn Fenty]]|[[No I.D.|Dion Wilson]]|[[Bibi Bourelly|Badriia Bourelly]]|[[James Fauntleroy]]|[[Jerry Butler|Jerry Butler II]]|[[Gamble and Huff|Kenneth Gamble]]|[[Gamble and Huff|Leon Huff]]|[[KRS-One|Lawrence Parker]]|Elton Newman|D'Artanian Stovall}}\n| extra7 = Jay Electronica\n| length7  = 3:27\n\n| title8 = Fruits of the Spirit\n| writer8 = {{hlist|Allah|Wilson|Rodney G. Massey}}\n| extra8 = [[No I.D.]]\n| length8  = 1:35\n\n| title9 = Ezekiel's Wheel\n| note9  = featuring The-Dream\n| writer9 = {{hlist|Allah|Nash|Carter|Fauntleroy|[[Robert Fripp]]|[[Brian Eno]]}}\n| extra9 = Jay Electronica\n| length9  = 6:48\n\n| title10 = A.P.I.D.T.A.\n| writer10 = {{hlist|Allah|Carter|Laura Manders|[[Mark Speer]]}}\n| extra10 = [[Khruangbin]]\n| length10  = 5:28\n}}\n\n'''Notes'''\n* All tracks except \"The Overwhelming Event\" and \"Fruits of the Spirit\" feature uncredited vocals by [[Jay-Z]].<!-- The other vocalists don't need to be included here; they're already in the personnel section -->\n* {{sup|{{note|a|[a]}}}} signifies a co-producer\n\n'''Sample credits'''\n* \"The Overwhelming Event\" contains elements of \"Th\u00e8me de Gerbier\", written and composed by [[\u00c9ric Demarsan]].\n* \"Ghost of Soulja Slim\" contains elements of \"[[Valley of the Dolls (film)#Soundtrack|Jennifer's French Movie]]\", written and composed by John Williams.\n* \"The Neverending Story\" contains elements of \"La Ca\u00edda\", written by [[Litto Nebbia|Felix Nebbia]] and Mirtha Defilpo, and performed by [[Litto Nebbia]].\n* \"Shiny Suit Theory\" contains elements of \"Ain't Got the Love (Of One Girl on My Mind)\", written by [[Barbara Mason]], and performed by The Ambassadors.\n* \"Flux Capacitor\" contains samples of \"[[Higher (Rihanna song)|Higher]]\", written by [[Rihanna|Robyn Fenty]], [[No I.D.|Dion Wilson]], [[Bibi Bourelly|Badriia Bourelly]], [[James Fauntleroy]], [[Jerry Butler|Jerry Butler II]], [[Gamble and Huff|Kenneth Gamble]] and [[Gamble and Huff|Leon Huff]], and performed by [[Rihanna]].\n* \"Fruits of the Spirit\" contains a sample of \"Because I Loved You\", performed by The Imaginations.\n* \"Ezekiel's Wheel\" contains elements of \"Evensong\", written by [[Robert Fripp]] and [[Brian Eno]], and composed by [[Fripp & Eno]].\n* \"A.P.I.D.T.A.\" contains elements of \"A Hymn\", written by [[Khruangbin|Laura Manders]] and [[Mark Speer]], and performed by [[Khruangbin]].\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits are adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref name=\"Tidal\"/>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Musicians'''\n*[[Louis Farrakhan]] \u2013 vocals {{small|(1, 2)}}\n*Larrance Dopson \u2013 keyboards {{small|(1, 2)}}\n*Khirye Tyler \u2013 guitar {{small|(1, 2)}}, organ {{small|(1, 2)}}, keyboards {{small|(1, 2)}}\n*Chris Payton \u2013 guitar {{small|(1, 2)}}, bass {{small|(1, 2)}}\n*[[The-Dream|Terius \"The-Dream\" Nash]] \u2013 featured vocals, {{small|(5, 9)}}, vocals {{small|(4)}}\n*[[James Blake (musician)|James Blake]] \u2013 vocals {{small|(6)}}\n*[[Travis Scott]] \u2013 featured vocals {{small|(2)}}, vocals {{small|(6)}}\n*Law Parker \u2013\u00a0vocals {{small|(7)}}\n*Steve Wyreman \u2013 bass {{small|(8)}}, keyboards {{small|(8)}}, guitar {{small|(8)}}\n*[[James Fauntleroy]] \u2013 vocals {{small|(9)}}\n*Jeymes Samuel \u2013 vocals {{small|(9)}}\n*Emory Jones \u2013 vocals {{small|(10)}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Technical'''\n*[[Young Guru]] \u2013 recording engineering, mixing {{small|(1\u20134, 6, 9)}}\n*Dylan Del-Olmo \u2013 recording engineering {{small|(1)}}, engineering {{small|(2)}}\n*Michael Chavarria \u2013 recording engineering {{small|(5)}}\n*Zach Steele \u2013 recording engineering {{small|(10)}}\n*LAW Parker \u2013 assistant recording engineering {{small|(3, 10)}}\n*Jaycen Joshua \u2013 mixing {{small|(7, 8, 10)}}\n*Mike Seaberg \u2013 assistant mixing {{small|(7, 8, 10)}}\n*Jacob Richards \u2013 assistant mixing {{small|(7, 8, 10)}}\n*Tony Dawsey \u2013 mastering engineering\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{album chart|Flanders|156|artist=Jay Electronica|album=A Written Testimony|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardCanada|43|M|url=https://www.fyimusicnews.ca/articles/2020/03/23/charts-march-22-2020|title=On The Charts: March 22, 2020|work=FYIMusicNews|artist=Jay Electronica|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Switzerland|65|artist=Jay Electronica|album=A Written Testimony|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|UK2|53|date=20200320|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Billboard200|12|artist=Jay Electronica|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardRandBHipHop|8|artist=Jay Electronica|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Rolling Stone Top 200|''Rolling Stone'' Top 200]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/charts/albums/2020-03-13/|title=Top 200 Albums|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n| 12\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Jay Electronica}}\n{{Jay-Z}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Written Testimony, A}}\n[[Category:2020 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by AraabMuzik]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Hit-Boy]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by The Alchemist (musician)]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by No I.D.]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Swizz Beatz]]\n[[Category:Roc Nation albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = A Written Testimony\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Jay Electronica]]\n| cover        = A Written Testimony cover art.jpg\n| border       = yes\n| alt          = \n| released     = March 13, 2020<ref name=\"NewRelease\"/>\n| recorded     = December 26, 2019 \u2013 February 6, 2020{{efn|Except \"Shiny Suit Theory\", recorded in November 2010}}\n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length       = 39:34\n| label        = [[Roc Nation]]\n| producer     =\n* Jay Electronica\n* [[Swizz Beatz]]\n* [[Hit-Boy]]\n* [[The Alchemist (musician)|The Alchemist]]\n* [[No I.D.]]\n* [[Khruangbin]]\n| year         = 2020\n| prev_title   = [[Act I: Eternal Sunshine (The Pledge)]]\n| prev_year    = 2007\n| next_title   =\n| next_year    =\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = A Written Testimony\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Shiny Suit Theory]]\n | single1date = November 15, 2010\n}}\n}}\n'''''A Written Testimony''''' ([[Arabic language|Arabic]]: ''\u0634\u0647\u0627\u062f\u0629 \u0645\u0643\u062a\u0648\u0628\u0629'') is the  debut studio album by American rapper [[Jay Electronica]]. The album was primarily recorded in 40 days, from December 2019 to February 2020, and was released on March 13, 2020. The album follows the release of his debut mixtape, ''[[Act I: Eternal Sunshine (The Pledge)]]'', almost 13 years earlier. Most of the album's tracks feature uncredited vocals by [[Jay-Z]], while [[Travis Scott]] and [[The-Dream]] make guest appearances. Production was primarily handled by Jay Electronica, who is credited on six out of ten tracks, along with [[Swizz Beats]], [[Hit-Boy]], [[No I.D.]], and [[Khruangbin]], among others.\n\n==Background and recording==\n[[File:Jay Electronica.jpg|thumb|left|Jay Electronica first announced a follow-up to ''[[Act I: Eternal Sunshine (The Pledge)]]'' in 2007, but didn't complete ''A Written Testimony'' until early 2020.]]\nJay Electronica's debut project ''[[Act I: Eternal Sunshine (The Pledge)]]'', released in July 2007, was meant to be the first part of a [[trilogy]], with the other planned installments being entitled ''Act II: Patents of Nobility (The Turn)'' and ''Act III: The Last Will & Testament of Timothy Elpadaro Thedford (The Prestige)''.<ref name=\"Vice\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/6ed3xk/the-prestige-the-five-percenters-and-why-jay-electronica-hasnt-released-his-debut-album|author=Ryan Bassil|date=October 23, 2013|accessdate=February 7, 2020|website=[[Vice Media|Vice UK]]|title=The Prestige, The Five Percenters, and Why Jay Electronica Hasn\u2019t Released His Debut Album}}</ref> In September 2007, Jay Electronica indicated that he planned to create ''Act II'' and ''Act III''.<ref name=\"2007Interview\">{{Cite web|date=September 27, 2007|accessdate=February 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121209081525/http://wmdeez.wordpress.com/2007/09/25/jay-electronica-interview/|archive-date=December 9, 2012|title=Jay Electronica Interview|website=Weapons of Mass Distraction|author=Andres Reyes|url=http://wmdeez.wordpress.com/2007/09/25/jay-electronica-interview/|url-status=dead}}</ref> Following the official release of his hit single \"[[Exhibit C]]\", Jay Electronica announced on [[Shade 45]] that ''Act II'' would be released on [[Christmas Day]] 2009; producer [[Just Blaze]] confirmed that the album would miss this date.<ref name=\"Timeline\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/jay-electronica-debut-album-timeline|title=The Long Road to Jay Electronica\u2019s Debut Album|date=February 25, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|author=Brad Callas}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, Jay Electronica stated that he was planning on doing collaborative projects with rappers [[Mos Def]], [[Lupe Fiasco]], and [[Nas]].<ref name=\"History\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/a-written-testimony-the-road-to-jay-electronicas-debut-album-news.103687.html|title=A Written Testimony: The Road To Jay Electronica's Debut Album|author=Robert Blair|date=February 15, 2020|accessdate=February 15, 2020|website=HotNewHipHop|archive-date=February 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215192545/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/a-written-testimony-the-road-to-jay-electronicas-debut-album-news.103687.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In August 2010, Jay Electronica stated that ''Act II'' would be released on his birthday September 19, 2010.<ref name=\"Timeline\"/> In November 2010, Jay Electronica signed to [[Roc Nation]] and released his first collaborative song with [[Jay-Z]], entitled \"[[Shiny Suit Theory]]\".<ref name=\"Timeline\"/><ref name=\"History\"/>\n\nJay Electronica announced that ''Act II'' was completed in 2011 and later shared a track list in 2012.<ref name=\"Vice\"/> The track list included guest appearances from Jay-Z, [[Kanye West]], [[Charlotte Gainsbourg]], [[The-Dream]], and [[Sean Combs]], among others.<ref name=\"Act2Tracks\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/47298-jay-electronica-shares-album-tracklist/|title=Jay Electronica Shares Album Tracklist|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=July 28, 2012|accessdate=February 7, 2020|author=Evan Minsker}}</ref> The album was never released.<ref name=\"Vice\"/> In 2013, Jay Electronica intended to include the song \"[[Control (Big Sean song)|Control]]\" on his album after [[Big Sean]] removed it from ''[[Hall of Fame (Big Sean album)|Hall of Fame]]''.<ref name=\"Control\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/52118-jay-electronica-wanted-control-for-his-album/|title=Jay Electronica Wanted \"Control\" for His Album|date=September 1, 2013|accessdate=February 16, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|author=Evan Minsker|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411203730/https://pitchfork.com/news/52118-jay-electronica-wanted-control-for-his-album/|archive-date=April 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> However, Big Sean instead released the song as a promotional single after [[Kendrick Lamar]] recorded his controversial verse for the song.<ref name=\"Control\"/> In 2014, Jay Electronica again announced that his album would be releasing that year.<ref name=\"History\"/> In 2017, Jay Electronica denounced the traditional roll-out of studio albums, stating \"[a]n album is something that was created by corporations as a product to make money.\"<ref name=\"History\"/>\n\nIn March 2019, Jay Electronica teased on [[Instagram]] that he may work with Jay-Z on his album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8503490/jay-electronica-teases-possible-jay-z-joint-collboration|title=Jay Electronica Hints at Possible Collaboration With Jay-Z|date=March 21, 2019|accessdate=February 7, 2020|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|author=Michael Saponara}}</ref> In April 2019, Zachary Schwartz of DJ Booth speculated that the collaborative album was ''Act III''.<ref name=\"Schwartz\">{{Cite web|url=https://djbooth.net/features/2019-04-05-jay-electronica-act-ii-found-in-plain-sight|title=We Found Jay Electronica\u2019s 'Act II'\u2014It\u2019s Been Hiding in Plain Sight|author=Zachary Schwartz|website=DJBooth|date=April 12, 2019|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref> On February 6, 2020, Jay Electronica announced that he completed his debut album ''A Written Testimony''.<ref name=\"Announce\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/jay-electronica-says-his-new-album-is-out-in-40-days/|title=Jay Electronica Says His New Album Is Out in 40 Days|author=Evan Minsker|date=February 7, 2020|accessdate=February 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207171923/https://pitchfork.com/news/jay-electronica-says-his-new-album-is-out-in-40-days/|archive-date=February 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Jay Electronica recorded the album in \"40 days and 40 nights\", beginning on December 26, 2019.<ref name=\"Announce\"/> Jay Electronica and Jay-Z recorded the final track \"A.P.I.D.T.A.\" on the night of January 26, 2020, when former NBA player [[Kobe Bryant]] died in a [[2020 Calabasas helicopter crash|helicopter crash]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/jay-electronica-jay-z-apidta-night-kobe-bryant-died|title=Jay Electronica and JAY-Z Made the Song \u201cA.P.I.D.T.A.\u201d on the Night Kobe Bryant Died|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020|author=Tara C. Mahadevan|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314140504/https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/jay-electronica-jay-z-apidta-night-kobe-bryant-died|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Jay Electronica set an initial release date of March 18, 2020, 40 days after recording was completed.<ref name=\"Announce\"/> In February 2020, radio host [[Angela Yee]], who formerly managed Jay Electronica, confirmed on ''[[The Breakfast Club (radio show)|The Breakfast Club]]'' that she had listened to the album and that \"Jay-Z is on much of the album.\"<ref name=\"Yee\">{{Cite web|url=https://allhiphop.com/news/angela-yee-confirms-jay-z-appears-on-much-of-jay-electronica-s-album-gives-details-about-the-release-IR-cXbZZs02obOyMZpEvBg|title=Angela Yee Confirms Jay-Z Appears On Much Of Jay Electronica's Album & Gives Details About The Release|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 15, 2020|author=Yohance Kyles|website=AllHipHop|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213204831/https://allhiphop.com/news/angela-yee-confirms-jay-z-appears-on-much-of-jay-electronica-s-album-gives-details-about-the-release-IR-cXbZZs02obOyMZpEvBg|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Release and promotion==\n[[File:A Written Testimony listening party poster.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Listening parties for the album were cancelled due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic]] (poster pictured).]]\nOn February 6, 2020, Jay Electronica announced ''A Written Testimony'' with a March 18, 2020 release date.<ref name=\"Announce\"/> In anticipation of the album's release, record producer [[Young Guru]] posted a picture of himself in the studio with Jay Electronica, Jay-Z and Lawrence \"Law\" Parker on March 10, 2020.<ref name=\"Parties\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/jay-electronica-jay-z-studio-pic-fuels-debut-album-anticipation|title=Tidal Announces Listening Events for Jay Electronica's Debut Album 'A Written Testimony' (UPDATE)|author=Joshua Espinoza|date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 11, 2020|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]}}</ref> That same day, [[Streaming media|streaming]] service [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]] announced three listening parties for the album.<ref name=\"Parties\"/> Tidal planned to host the listening parties on March 12 in [[Los Angeles]], [[New York City]], and Jay Electronica's hometown of [[New Orleans]].<ref name=\"Parties\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9332435/jay-electronica-a-written-testimony-tidal-listening-sessions|title=Jay Electronica Album Listening Sessions Are Finally Happening in These Cities|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=March 11, 2020|date=March 11, 2020|author=Carl Lamarre|url-status=live|archive-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311224551/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9332435/jay-electronica-a-written-testimony-tidal-listening-sessions}}</ref> On March 11, 2020, Yee confirmed on ''The Breakfast Club'' that the album would be released on March 13, 2020 after the listening parties.<ref name=\"NewRelease\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2ohlDtYcaAQ|title=6ix9ine's Prison Release Date Has Been Set Early For Being A 'Model Prisoner'|website=[[YouTube]]|author=[[The Breakfast Club (radio show)|The Breakfast Club]]|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On March 12, 2020, [[Apple Music]] revealed the track listing for ''A Written Testimony'' through [[Twitter]]. The track listing, written in the [[Arabic language]], included ten tracks with [[guest appearance]]s from [[Travis Scott]] and The-Dream.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/jay-electronica-a-written-testimony-tracklist|title=Jay Electronica Shares Tracklist for Upcoming Debut Album 'A Written Testimony'|author=Tara C. Mahadevan|publisher=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Tracklist\">{{cite web|url=https://hiphop-n-more.com/2020/03/jay-electronica-a-written-testimony-track-list-stream/|title=Jay Electronica Reveals 'A Written Testimony' Track List|website=HipHop-N-More|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/everything-we-know-about-jay-electronica-s-new-album-a-written-testimony-cover-art-tracklist-features-producers-release-date|title=Here\u2019s Everything We Know About Jay Electronica\u2019s New Album \u2018A Written Testimony\u2019|website=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> After the track list was revealed, the listening parties were cancelled due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic]] and Tidal revealed the album's cover art.<ref name=\"Tracklist\"/>\n\nIn November 2010, Jay Electronica released his first collaborative song with Jay-Z entitled \"Shiny Suit Theory\" after signing to Roc Nation.<ref name=\"History\"/> In July 2012, a track list for ''Act II: Patents of Nobility (The Turn)'' was revealed that included a song titled \"Dinner at Tiffanys (The Shiny Suit Theory)\" featuring Gainsbourg, Jay-Z and The-Dream.<ref name=\"Act2Tracks\"/> In September 2018, the original version of the song was rereleased exclusively to Tidal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hiphop-n-more.com/2018/09/jay-electronica-officially-releases-shiny-suit-theory-feat-jay-z-the-dream/|title=Jay Electronica Officially Releases 'Shiny Suit Theory' Feat. Jay-Z & The-Dream|publisher=HipHop-N-More|date=September 17, 2018|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The song was included on the track list for ''A Written Testimony'' revealed in March 2020, with only The-Dream listed as a featured artist.<ref name=\"Tracklist\"/>\n\n==Controversy==\n[[File:Louis Farrakhan 2018.jpg|thumb|left|200px|[[Louis Farrakhan]], who has been designated as a hate extremist by the [[Southern Poverty Law Center|SPLC]], is featured on the album.]]\nOn the track \"The Ghost of Soulja Slim\", Jay Electronica references the [[Synagogue of Satan]] and his ex-girlfriend [[Kate Rothschild]].<ref name=\"Rosenberg\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/peter-rosenberg-responds-to-jay-electronica-synagogue-of-satan-lyric|title=Peter Rosenberg Speaks More on Jay Electronica Defending 'Synagogue of Satan' Lyric|author=FNR Tigg|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Jay Electronica had previously rapped about the Synagogue of Satan on 2014 track \"Better Tune in with the Infinite\".<ref name=\"Rosenberg\"/> Rothschild has also been the subject of multiple [[Anti-Semitism|anti-Semitic]] conspiracy theories.<ref name=\"JP\"/> American radio personality [[Peter Rosenberg]] accused Jay Electronica of anti-Semitism for his Synagogue of Satan references.<ref name=\"Rosenberg\"/> Jay Electronica responded by accusing Rosenberg of \"clout chasing\" and invited him to a public forum with theological scholars to discuss the lyrics.<ref name=\"Rosenberg\"/> Jay Electronica also stated that he stood behind \"every single word\" on the album.<ref name=\"Rosenberg\"/> FNR Tigg of ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' defended \"The Ghost of Soulja Slim\", writing that the particular line was not anti-Semetic but that Jay Electronica was \"finding a clever way to vent about a personal vendetta he had against [Rothschild] who he feels aided in helping the media assassinate his character.\"<ref name=\"Rosenberg\"/>\n\nLee Harpin of ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]'' also noted the lyrics \"Satan struck [[State of Palestine|Palestine]] with yet another mortar\" from the track \"Fruits of the Spirit\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/world/new-hip-hop-jay-electronica-album-antisemitism-storm-synagogue-of-satan-louis-farrakhan-1.498215|title=New hip hop album causes antisemitism storm with 'synagogue of Satan' reference|author=Lee Harpin|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020|website=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]}}</ref> Gabe Friedman of ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'' highlighted the album's inclusion of vocals from [[Louis Farrakhan]],<ref name=\"JP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Antisemitism/Rapper-Jay-Electronica-sparks-antisemitism-controversy-621379|title=Rapper Jay Electronica sparks antisemitism controversy|website=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020|author=Gabe Friedman}}</ref> the leader of the [[Nation of Islam]] who has been labelled as an extremist by the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] due to anti-Semitic and [[Black supremacy|black supremacist]] views.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/extremist-files/individual/louis-farrakhan|title=Louis Farrakhan \u2013 Southern Poverty Law Center|website=[[Southern Poverty Law Center]]|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Featured artist Jay-Z has also been previously cautioned by the [[Anti-Defamation League]] in 2017 for controversial lyrics.<ref name=\"JP\"/>\n\nSoon after release, Jay Electronica was also embroiled in an online dispute with American rapper-journalist [[Joe Budden]].<ref name=\"Budden\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/jay-electronica-joe-budden-beef/|title=Jay Electronica & Joe Budden Have Beef Over 'A Written Testimony'|accessdate=March 20, 2020|date=March 18, 2020|author=Feleg Tesema|website=[[Highsnobiety]]}}</ref> On his podcast, Budden criticized the album and stated that \"Jay Electronica got smacked around by JAY-Z\".<ref name=\"Budden\"/> Jay Electronica reacted by denouncing Budden's rap career, however an old video recorded by Yee surfaced that showed Jay Electronica praising Budden as an [[Master of ceremonies|MC]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.okayplayer.com/news/joe-budden-jay-electronica-twitter-feud.html|title=Joe Budden Addresses Jay Electronica Twitter Back And Forth On Podcast|author=Elijah C. Watson|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020|website=OkayPlayer}}</ref>\n{{clear}}<!--Only pushes down by one line-->\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 82/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/a-written-testimony/jay-electronica|title=A Written Testimony by Jay Electronica Reviews and Tracks|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/a-written-testimony-mw0003368165|title=A Written Testimony \u2013 Jay Electronica|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|last=Thomas|first=Fred|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev2score = A\u2212<ref name=\"COS\">{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/03/album-review-jay-electronica-a-written-testimony/|title=Jay Electronica Finally Delivers on A Written Testimony|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=Grove|first=Rashad|date=March 15, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3score = B+<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/music/music-reviews/jay-electronica-a-written-testimony-ew-review/|title=Jay Electronica's A Written Testimony is a righteous step forward: Review|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Moore|first=Marcus J.|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev4score = 7/10<ref name=\"exclaim\">{{cite web|url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/jay_electronica-a_written_testimony|title=Jay Electronica: A Written Testimony|website=[[Exclaim!]]|last=Harmony|first=A.|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[HipHopDX]]''\n| rev5score = 4.0/5<ref name=\"HHDX\">{{cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/reviews/id.3636/title.review-jay-electronica-basks-in-jay-zs-shadow-on-debut-album-a-written-testimony|title=Review: Jay Electronica Basks In JAY-Z's Shadow On Debut Album 'A Written Testimony'|website=[[HipHopDX]]|last=Kenny|first=Brody|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/jay-electronica-a-written-testimony-review-2626202|title=Jay Electronica \u2013 'A Written Testimony' review: mythical rapper's Jay-Z collab isn't the revelation fans had hoped for|website=[[NME]]|last=Balram|first=Dhruva|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7score = 8.4/10<ref name=\"pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/jay-electronica-a-written-testimony/|title=Jay Electronica: A Written Testimony Album Review|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Pearce|first=Sheldon|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n''A Written Testimony'' was met with widespread acclaim from critics. At Metacritic, which assigns a weighted average rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, this release received an average score of 82, based on seven reviews.<ref name=\"MC\"/>\n\nRashad Grove of ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' praised the album as \"one hell of a promising effort that was well worth the wait\", further stating, \"The skillset of Jay Electronica as both an MC and a producer is on full display, even when he does seemingly play [[Robin (character)|Robin]] to Jay-Z's [[Batman|Dark Knight]] on his own project.\"<ref name=\"COS\"/> A. Harmony of ''[[Exclaim!]]'' hailed it as \"a solid effort that makes good on promises set by Electronica's earlier work: thumping, vintage beats; dense rhymes that shimmer with vivid imagery; clever references to the Nation of Islam.\"<ref name=\"exclaim\"/> ''[[HipHopDX]]''{{'s}} Brody Kenny felt that the album was worth the anticipation, describing it as a \"summation of why so many people have revered Jay Electronica for so long.\"<ref name=\"HHDX\"/> Writing for ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', Marcus J. Moore called it \"an accomplished album with decent rewind factor, but it feels somewhat hampered by the seismic impact of the rapper's work a decade ago.\"<ref name=\"EW\"/> In his review for ''[[NME]]'', Dhruva Balram noted that Jay Electronica and Jay-Z \"exchange epic verses in a style that's inevitably similar to [[Raekwon]] and [[Ghostface Killah]] on ''[[Only Built 4 Cuban Linx...|Only Built 4 Cuban Linx]]''\", however, he concluded that the album \"is nothing spectacular; it won't shift or affect cultural discourse.\"<ref name=\"NME\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Track listing==\nCredits are adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref name=\"Tidal\">{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/134189334/credits|title=Credits / A Written Testimony / J A Y E L E C T R O N I C A|publisher=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 39:34\n| title_width = 30%\n| writing_width = 50%\n| extra_width = 20%\n