age, 2020)]]<ref name=\" World Bank and International Financial Corporation \">{{cite web |url=http://www.doingbusiness.org/data/exploreeconomies/algeria |title=Ease of Doing Business in Algeria |publisher=Doingbusiness.org |accessdate=2017-01-24 }}</ref>\n|exports              = {{increase}} $34.37 billion (2017 est.)<ref name=\"CIAWFAG\"/>\n|export-goods         = [[petroleum]], [[natural gas]] and [[petroleum products]] 94% (2017)<ref name=\" Observatory of Economic Complexity, which \">{{cite web |url=https://oec.world/en/profile/country/dza/ |title=Algeria Exports |publisher= oec.world |accessdate=2019-09-22 }}</ref>\n|export-partners      = {{plainlist|\n*{{flag|Italy}} 17.4%\n*{{flag|Spain}} 13%\n*{{flag|France}} 11.9%\n*{{flag|United States}} 9.4%\n*{{flag|Brazil}} 6.2%\n*{{flag|Netherlands}} 5.2% \n*(2017)<ref name=\"CIAWFAG\"/>}}\n|imports              = {{decrease}} $48.54 billion (2017 est.)<ref name=\"CIAWFAG\"/>\n|import-goods         = [[capital goods]], [[foodstuff]]s, [[consumer goods]]\n|import-partners      = {{plainlist|\n*{{flag|China}} 18.2%\n*{{flag|France}} 9.2%\n*{{flag|Italy}} 8%\n*{{flag|Germany}} 7%\n*{{flag|Spain}} 6.9%\n*{{flag|Turkey}} 4.4% \n*(2017)<ref name=\"CIAWFAG\"/>}}\n|current account      = {{increase}} \u2212$22.1 billion (2017 est.)<ref name=\"CIAWFAG\"/>\n|FDI                  = {{plainlist|\n*{{increase}} $29.05 billion (31 December 2017 est.)<ref name=\"CIAWFAG\"/>\n*{{decrease}} Abroad: $1.893 billion (31 December 2017 est.)<ref name=\"CIAWFAG\"/>}}\n|gross external debt  = {{increaseNegative}} $6.26 billion (31 December 2017 est.)<ref name=\"CIAWFAG\"/>\n|debt                 = {{increaseNegative}} 27.5% of GDP (2017 est.)<ref name=\"CIAWFAG\"/> {{refn|group=note|data cover central government debt as well as debt issued by subnational entities and intra-governmental debt}}\n|revenue              = 54.15 billion (2017 est.)<ref name=\"CIAWFAG\"/>\n|expenses             = 70.2 billion (2017 est.)<ref name=\"CIAWFAG\"/>\n|balance              = \u22129.6% (of GDP) (2017 est.)<ref name=\"CIAWFAG\"/>\n|aid                  = \n|credit               =\n|reserves             = {{decrease}} $97.89 billion (31 December 2017 est.)<ref name=\"CIAWFAG\"/>\n|cianame              = ag\n|spelling             = \n}}\n[[Image:2006Algerian exports.PNG|thumb|Algerian exports in 2006]]\n[[Image:B\u00e9ja\u00efa port.JPG|thumb|View of the oil port of [[B\u00e9ja\u00efa]].]]\n\nThe economy of Algeria expanded by 4% in 2014, up from 2.8% in 2013. Growth was driven mainly by the recovering oil and gas sector and further economic expansion of 3.9% is forecast in 2015 and 4.0% in 2016.<ref>http://www.africaneconomicoutlook.org/en/country-notes/north-africa/algeria/ Algeria: African Economic Outlook, May 2015</ref>\n\nIn 2012, [[Algeria]]'s economy grew by 2.5%, up slightly from 2.4% in 2011. Excluding hydrocarbons, growth has been estimated at 5.8% (up from 5.7% in 2011). Inflation is increasing and is estimated at 8.9% (up from 4.49% in 2011). Despite the financial authorities\u2019 good performance, thanks to modernisation reforms, the budget deficit widened to 3.3% of GDP in 2012 (as against 1.3% in 2011) due to the continuation of the expansionary fiscal policy initiated in 2011 to meet strong social demands in terms of purchasing power, jobs and housing. The oil and gas sector is the country's main source of revenues, generated about 70% of total budget receipts. The economy is projected to grow by 3.2% in 2013 and by 4.0% in 2014.\nThe country's external position remained comfortable in 2012, with a trade surplus of about US$27.18 billion. The current-account surplus is estimated at 8.2% of GDP and official foreign-exchange reserves have been estimated at US$190.7 billion at end-December 2012, or the equivalent of more than three years of imports of non-factor goods and services. Oil and gas export earnings made up more than 97% of total exports.\n\nAlgeria has enormous possibilities to boost its economic growth, including huge foreign-exchange reserves derived from oil and gas. A development strategy targeting stronger, sustained growth would create more jobs, especially for young people, and alleviate the housing shortage the country is facing. The national strategic option is therefore to revitalise the process intended to diversify the economy starting with the non-oil sector while deepening the reforms needed for the structural transformation of the economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afdb.org/en/countries/north-africa/algeria/algeria-economic-outlook/|title=Algeria Economic Outlook|website=African Development Bank|accessdate=30 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Historical trend==\nThe total imports and exports on the eve of the French invasion (in 1830) did not exceed \u00a3175,000. By 1850, the figures had reached \u00a35,000,000; in 1868, \u00a312,000,000; in 1880, \u00a317,000,000; and in 1890, \u00a320,000,000. From this point progress was slower and the figures varied considerably year by year. In 1905 the total value of the foreign trade was \u00a324,500,000. About five-sixths of the trade is with or via France, into which country several Algerian goods have been admitted duty-free since 1851, and all since 1867. French goods, except [[sugar]], have been admitted into Algeria without payment of duty since 1835. After the 1892 increase of the French minimum tariff which applied to Algeria for the first time, foreign trade greatly diminished.{{Citation needed|date=July 2009}}\n\nGDP per capita grew 40% in the 1960s, reaching a peak growth of 538% in the 1970s.<ref>[http://earthtrends.wri.org/text/economics-business/variable-638.html GDP: GDP per capita, current US dollars<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090220000000/http://earthtrends.wri.org/text/economics-business/variable-638.html |date=February 20, 2009 }}</ref> Growth collapsed to 9.7% in the turbulent 1980s. Failure of timely reforms by successive governments caused the current GDP per capita to shrink by 28% in the 1990s.\n\nThis is a chart of trend of gross domestic product of Algeria at market prices [http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2006/01/data/dbcselm.cfm?G=2001 estimated] by the International Monetary Fund.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year || Gross Domestic Product<br>million Algerian dinars || US Dollar Exchange<br> Algerian dinars || Inflation Index<br/> (2000=100) || Per Capita Income<br/> (as % of USA)\n|-\n| 1980 || 162,500 || 3.83 || 9.30 || 18.51\n|-\n| 1985 || 291,600 || 4.77 || 14 || 15.55\n|-\n| 1990 || 554,400 || 12.19 || 22 || 10.65\n|-\n| 1995 || 2,004,990 || 47.66 || 73 || 5.39\n|-\n| 2000 || 4,123,514 || 75.31 || 100 || 5.17\n|-\n| 2005 || 7,493,000 || 73.44 || 114 || 7.43\n|}\n\nFor purchasing power parity comparisons, the US dollar is exchanged at 70.01 Algerian dinars only (updated May 24, 2007). Average wages in 2007 hover around US$18\u201322 per day.\n\n[[Image:A highway bridge near A\u00efn Turk, Algeria 02966.jpg|thumb|200px|New bridge construction near [[A\u00efn Turk, Bou\u00efra|A\u00efn Turk]].]] \nBurdened with a heavy [[foreign debt]], Algiers concluded a one-year standby arrangement with the [[International Monetary Fund]] in April 1994 and the following year signed onto a three-year extended fund facility which ended 30 April 1998. In March 2006, [[Russia]] agreed to erase $4.74 billion of Algeria's Soviet-era debt during a visit by President [[Vladimir Putin]] to the country, the first by a Russian leader in half a century. In return, president [[Abdelaziz Bouteflika]] agreed to buy $7.5 billion worth of combat planes, air-defence systems and other arms from Russia, according to the head of Russia's state arms exporter [[Rosoboronexport]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Russia agrees Algeria arms deal, writes off debt | publisher=Reuters | date=2006-03-11 | url=http://za.today.reuters.com/news/NewsArticle.aspx?type=businessNews&storyID=2006-03-11T082958Z_01_BAN130523_RTRIDST_0_OZABS-ECONOMY-RUSSIA-ALGERIA-20060311.XML | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060528075210/http://za.today.reuters.com/news/newsArticle.aspx?type=businessNews | archivedate=2006-05-28 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=La Russie efface la dette alg\u00e9rienne | publisher=Radio France International |date=March 10, 2006 | url=http://www.rfi.fr/actufr/articles/075/article_42379.asp|language=fr}}</ref> \n\nSome progress on economic reform, [[Paris Club]] [[debt rescheduling]]s in 1995 and 1996, and oil and gas sector expansion contributed to a recovery in growth since 1995, reducing [[inflation]] to approximately 1% and narrowing the [[budget deficit]]. Algeria's economy has grown at about 4% annually since 1999. The country's foreign debt has fallen from a high of $28 billion in 1999 to its current level of $5 billion. The spike in oil prices in 1999\u20132000 and the government's tight fiscal policy, as well as a large increase in the trade surplus and the near tripling of foreign exchange reserves has helped the country's finances. However, an ongoing drought, the after effects of the floods of 10 November 2001 and an uncertain oil market made prospects for 2002-03 more problematic. The government has pledged to continue its efforts to diversify the economy by attracting foreign and domestic investment outside the energy sector.\n\n[[Image:Tlemcen Hotel Zianides.jpg|thumb|200px|Hotel Zianides in [[Tlemcen]].]] \n[[Abdelaziz Bouteflika|President Bouteflika]] has announced sweeping economic reforms, which, if implemented, will significantly restructure the economy. Still, the economy remains heavily dependent on volatile oil and gas revenues. The government has continued efforts to diversify the economy by attracting foreign and domestic investment outside the energy sector, but has had little success in reducing high unemployment and improving living standards. Other priority areas include banking reform, improving the investment environment, and reducing government bureaucracy.\n\nThe government has announced plans to sell off state enterprises: sales of a national cement factory and steel plant have been completed and other industries are up for offer. In 2001, Algeria signed an Association Agreement with the [[European Union]]. In June 1987, Algeria started accession negotiations for entry into the [[World Trade Organization]], but negotiations ceased in \t 2014.\n\n== Data ==\nThe following table shows the main economic indicators in 1980\u20132017. Inflation under 5% is in green.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2018/01/weodata/weorept.aspx?sy=1980&ey=2023&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=612&s=NGDP_RPCH%2CPPPGDP%2CPPPPC%2CPCPIPCH%2CLUR%2CGGXWDG_NGDP&grp=0&a=&pr.x=11&pr.y=14|title=Report for Selected Countries and Subjects|website=www.imf.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-21}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!Year\n!GDP<br /><small>(in bil. US$ PPP)</small>\n!GDP per capita<br /><small href=\"Paris\">(in US$ PPP)</small>\n!GDP growth<br /><small>(real)</small>\n!Inflation rate<br /><small>(in Percent)</small>\n!Unemployment <br /><small>(in Percent)</small>\n!Government debt<br /><small>(in % of GDP)</small>\n|-\n|1980\n|86.6\n|4,641\n|{{decrease}}\u22125.4 %\n|{{IncreaseNegative}}9.7 %\n|15.8 %\n|n/a\n|-\n|1981\n|{{increase}}97.6\n|{{increase}}5,069\n|{{increase}}3.0 %\n|{{IncreaseNegative}}14.6 %\n|{{decreasePositive}}15.4 %\n|n/a\n|-\n|1982\n|{{Increase}}110.2\n|{{Increase}}5,550\n|{{increase}}6.4 %\n|{{IncreaseNegative}}6.7 %\n|{{decreasePositive}}15.0 %\n|n/a\n|-\n|1983\n|{{Increase}}120.8\n|{{Increase}}5,887\n|{{Increase}}5.4 %\n|{{IncreaseNegative}}7.8 %\n|{{decreasePositive}}14.3 %\n|n/a\n|-\n|1984\n|{{Increase}}132.1\n|{{Increase}}6,237\n|{{increase}}5.6 %\n|{{IncreaseNegative}}6.3 %\n|{{IncreaseNegative}}16.5 %\n|n/a\n|-\n|1985\n|{{Increase}}143.9\n|{{Increase}}6,483\n|{{Increase}}5.6 %\n|{{IncreaseNegative}}10.4 %\n|{{Incr